Forensics Evidence Collection > [T1]: Lab - Evidence Collection: KAPE

3-Acquire Use Kroll Artifact Parser and Extractor (KAPE) to acquire a triage image.

Kape is a very popular tool for acquiring a triage image. As a reminder, a triage image is nothing other than a collection of important forensic artifacts (files and directories).

 

Kape directory - (zoom in)

  1. Documentation: tool documentation.
  2. Modules: a list of custom-ready scripts to process artifacts in a specific way (e.g., extract "log on" events only from windows event logs and export it to a CSV file.
  3. Targets: a list of artifacts to collect. This could be a single artifact (e.g., windows event logs) or a template for a group of artifacts (e.g., Basic Collection).
  4. Get-KAPEUpdate.ps1: powershell script to update kape to the latest version.
  5. gkape: GUI version of KAPE
  6. kape: command-line version of KAPE.

Run the GUI version gkape as an administrator. The main interface is split into two sections "1. Targets" & "2. Modules".

 

Kape main interface - (zoom-in)

Let's start with the "Target section". 

 

Targets interface - (zoom-in)

  1. Target source: the drive or directory which contains the files you want to collect.
  2. Target Destination: the drive or directory to save the produced image.
  3. Flush option: wipes out the destination directory/drive before acquisition. Recommended read.
  4. Targets: what artifacts to collect?
  5. Output format:  zip archive, vhd, or vhdx.
  6. Base name: the name of the output file.
  7. Deduplicate: removes duplications (e.g., a single artifact can be present in many targets. For example, windows event logs exists in both targets; Basic Collection and SANS_Triage.
  8. Process VSCs: process files included in Windows backup known as Volume shadow copies (VSCs).
  9. Transfer: save the output image to a remote network location such as SFTP server or an Azure instance.
  10. Transfer options: remote network share configurations.
  11. Current command line: displays the actual command line KAPE will execute, reflecting the selected options.

Once you configure the tool, click the "execute" button in the bottom-right corner. A command line will open and run the equivalent CMD command.

 

kape command-line - (zoom-in)

Next, you will be presented with an executive summary stating the output file location and showing any acquisition errors.

 

kape command-line - (zoom-in)

  1. Path of the output file 'D:\2022-10-9Y184137_triage-image.zip'
  2. Targets that KAPE could not acquire.

Browsing to the output path, you will see two files.

 

Output path - (zoom-in)

  1. The first file contains a copy of the text written to the console (i.e., console output).
  2. The second file is the output triage image.

Inside the zip archive, you will find that the tool replicates the directory structure of collected data. For example, if the tool was configured to copy "C:\Program Files\example", it will create a directory named "C", a sub-direcotry called "Program Files," and place the "example" right there. In other words, it will maintain the same directory structure of collected files and directories.

 

data presented in the container - (zoom in)

  1. The first section shows collected artifacts (actual files copied).
  2. The second section contains a CSV log file for collected/skipped artifacts.

 

Note that Targets and Modules are independent. You can select targets or modules, or both of them. You will use the Modules section if you need to quickly parse a specific artifact and check for low-hanging fruits (without copying the actual artifact).

 

Module interface - (zoom-in)

  1. Source and destination, similar to the Target section.
  2. Modules to execute.
  3. Export format: output format.
  4. Module variables: customize modules scripts.
  5. Current command line: displays the actual command line KAPE will execute, reflecting the selected options.
  6. Execute: start acqusition.

KAPE command-line interface will pop up:

 

kape command-line - (zoom-in)

The output files will be saved to the path set in "Module Destination".
